<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>New Mexico's solar resource is among the strongest in the United States, with the state receiving an average of 5.8 peak sun hours per day throughout the year. This solar irradiance translates to exceptional energy production potential, with a typical 1kW solar system generating approximately 1,600-1,800 kWh annually. The state's high elevation, ranging from 2,800 feet to over 13,000 feet above sea level, combined with clear, dry air and minimal cloud cover, creates optimal conditions for photovoltaic energy generation.</p>

<p>Solar panels in New Mexico benefit from the state's low humidity and minimal air pollution, which can reduce solar panel efficiency in other regions. The intense UV radiation at high altitude actually increases solar panel output, while the cooler ambient temperatures help maintain optimal operating conditions. During peak summer months, solar systems in New Mexico can produce 20-30% more energy than the same systems would generate in less favorable climates. Cities like Albuquerque, Las Cruces, and Santa Fe consistently rank among the top metropolitan areas nationwide for solar energy potential, making residential solar installations highly productive investments.</p>

<p>The seasonal variation in solar production is relatively modest compared to northern states, with winter months still providing substantial energy generation. Even during December and January, New Mexico solar systems typically produce 60-70% of their peak summer output, ensuring year-round energy production that can offset a significant portion of household electricity consumption. This consistent production profile makes solar financial projections more predictable and reliable for New Mexico homeowners considering renewable energy investments.</p>

